  "text": "Tumor associated macrophages (TAMs) have been generally considered as M2-polarized. [CITATION_1] These cells have been shown to promote tumor growth and angiogenesis. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] To test whether the colony macrophages could function as M2 macrophages in the tumor microenvironment, we coinjected these cells together with RM1 cells (murine prostate cancer cells) into wild type C57BL/6 mice. Resulting subcutaneous tumors were palpable by 6 days after injection and reached terminal point around day 12.",
